Human Resource Analysis

Ekta Raj

August 29, 2017

This report explores a dataset containing satisfaction level, salary_level, years spend in the company and other attributes for approximately 15000 human resource working in an organization to discover the factors which are responsible for causing an employee to leave his job.

Univariate Analysis

Q1. What is the structure of the dataset?

There are 14999 observations in this dataset with 11 variables like: satisfaction_level, last_evaluation, number_project, avg_monthly_hours, time_spend_company, Work_accident, left, promotion_last_5years, department, salaryand daily_work_hour

Understanding each variable:

  • satisfaction_level: a feeling of fulfilment or enjoyment that a person derives from their job.
    • It is a continous value measured on the scale of 0-1, in increasing order.
  • last_evaluation: assessment of employees last performance.
    • It is a continous value measured on the scale of 0-1, in increasing order.

  • number_project: number of project a particular employee has worked on.

  • avg_monthly_hours: average monthly hours spend by an employee at work.

  • daily_work_hours: number of hours an employee works everyday.
    • It is a derived variable, calculated by dividing avg_monthly_hours by 22 assuming 22 is the number of days an employee works in a month.

  • time_spend_company: number of years spend in the company.

  • work_accident: if an employee met any accident at work.
    • It is a factored variable having 0 false and 1 for true.
  • left: if an employee still working or has left his job.
    • It is a factored variable having 0 false and 1 for true.
  • promotion_last_5years: if an employee has been promoted in last 5 years or not.
    • It is a factored variable having 0 false and 1 for true.

  • department: department to which an employee belongs to, like, sales, account, IT, management etc.

  • salary: salary received by each employee, low, medium or high.
    • Out of these variables, salary is an ordered variable having low < medium < high levels.

Other obsevations:

  • The mean satisfaction_level is 0.612. It is as low as 0.09 and as high as 1.
  • The mean last_evaluation is 0.71. Most people are average performers.
  • Only 2% employees got promoted in last 5 years.
  • Most number of employees work in sales department and those in marketting are least in number.
  • Daily working hour ranges from 5 hours to 15 hours.
  • Time spent in company ranges from 1 to 10 years. Most people spend atleast 3 years in a company.

Q1. What is the main feature(s) of interest in the dataset?

Almost all the features of this dataset are important to evalaute the tendency of an employee to leave his job. The main features of interest are satisfaction_level and left(did he leave or not). All other features contribute to the satisfaction level.

Q2. What other features in the dataset will help

support the investigation of feature(s) of interest?

Satisfaction_level is influenced by daily_working_hour, number_of_projects, last_evaluation, department in which he works, salary. Thus all these features would help to investigate the faetures of interest.

Q3. Did you create any new variables from existing

variables in the dataset?

Yes, I have derived daily_work_hour variable by dividing avg_monthly_hours by 22 assuming 22 is the total number of days an employee works in a month.

The assumption of number of days is made on the basis that office is off on weekdays. There are only 5 working days in a week.

The predefined avg_monthly_hours does not give a vivid description of the number of hours an employee has to work. Thus, I felt the need of daily_work_hour variable.

Q4. Of the features you investigated, were there

any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

We found that there is no employee who left in the first and ninth year of his job. Yes, I factored the variables like left, promotion_last_5years, work_accident because these have boolean values (0 or 1). Factoring them makes ploting and summaries easier. They have been reconverted into numeric form when required.

The salary variable has also been factored as well as ordered in low < medium < high levels.

However, I also found that people have left jobs across all satisfaction levels.50 percent of the people who left had satisfaction level below mean.

Satisfaction_level and daily working hour is also negatively correlated i.e which is reasonable. The satisfaction_level and left is found to be negatively correlated but it is still the strongest relation because as satisfaction level increases number of exits decreases and visa versa. However there are other features that affect satisfaction level and left individually.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions

People receiving high salary, having more that 75% satisfaction level and scoring more that 75% in last_evaluation have left job after serving the company for 5 years. Surprising, none of them have been promoted in last 5 years. It is possible that they are among the top notch of the company from the beginning.

Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

Yes, I have created a matematical model that predicts possible exits.

Predicting who are likely to leave.

Considering the above analysis, we know some of the scenarios which cause people to leave their job.

Using some mathemetical conditions and bringing all the scenarios together,if we find all the conditions at one place we can predict that who are and how many employees likely to leave their jobs.

The conditions I used are:

  • left == 0 &
  • satisfaction_level < 0.5 &
  • salary == low | salary ==medium) &
  • time_spend_company == 3 &
  • (daily_work_hour==7 |daily_work_hour==12)&
  • (last_evaluation <= 0.5 | last_evaluation>=0.75)&
  • number_project == 2

These conditions are found to be true for 201 observations.

The limitation of this prediction is that it does not involves job leaving tendency of highly paid and efficient employees. Only the conditions where exits are more frequent have been taken into account.

Reflection

  • The human resource dataset contains 14999 observations and 10 variables originally. I was facsinated to know what makes employees to make a big decision of leavinf or changing their jobs. I started with making some adjustment to the dataset to simplify the analysis and to get better results. I factored and ordered some variables like department, salary, left, promotion_last_5years etc, so that summaries could give informative results.

  • Then I derived daily_working_hour variable from average_monthly_hours. I went on with analysing each varible separately to see the variation within each variable.

  • I found that more than 50% of employee are moderately satisfied. Not even low performers but high performers are also leaving jobs. Most people leave job after completing 3 years in the same company.

  • Very low percentage of employees were promoted in last 5 years.

  • Moving on, I analysed what variations any two variables show with repect to each other.The both negative and positive correlations are observed between many variable but some how they are not very strong. With respect to left: satisfaction_level, work_accident, and promotion_last_5years are negatively correlated while others are positively correlated(with respect to left). Satisfaction_level and promotions as well as number_project and daily_working_hours are positively correlated.

  • I had a presumption that satisfaction_level and left would influenced each other very strongly but I found this idea collapsing during this analysis.

  • Lastly I examined the multiple variables altogether and found some interesting facts that number of exits is propotional to the number of employees working in that department.Highly paid employees are least in number to leave.Some efficient employees with very low satisfaction level and other with high satisfaction level have left job in both the scenarios.

  • I also answered some interesting questions like: How many years an employee spends in a company before leaving, given that salary is high, satisfaction level is above 75%, efficiency is above 75% ? Answer is- 5years.

  • I created a mathematical model that predicts possible future exits from the company. Certain conditions/criteria are found to be true for 201 observations.

  • The limitation of this prediction is that it does not involves job leaving tendency of highly paid employees. Only the conditions where exits are more frequent have been taken into account.Limited knowledge about the source of the dataset is also a drawback.

  • I faced some difficulty while calculating correlation between variables because some variables were numerical while other were factored or ordered. I converted them accordingly.

  • I found success in deriving new veriables, answering some question that came to my mind and also in predicted the exits that are most likely in near future.

  • There is a scope for future analysis in this dataset. I would like to create a stronger model to predict the number of exits more accurately.

  • I would like to find out why some top performers receiving high salary have satisfaction_level as low as 0.09.

  • It would have been better if there were more features into picture which affects the satisfaction level like working conditions, interaction within the hierarchy of supervisiors, amenitites and allowances.
